 {"id":"frankenpandas-u6zn","title":"fd90.14: SqlReadOptions::schema for cross-schema reads","description":"fd90 sub-bead: wire SqlConnection::supports_schemas / default_schema into read_sql_table by adding SqlReadOptions::schema: Option<String>. When schema is Some(s) AND conn.supports_schemas(), the SELECT statement targets schema.table (each part quoted via conn.quote_identifier). When schema is None, falls back to bare table name (current behavior). Backends that don't support schemas (SQLite) ignore schema=Some — bead body documents that pandas/SQLAlchemy raises NotImplementedError there but we choose silent ignore + DISCREPANCIES doc to avoid breaking SQLite users. Phase 2 of fd90.13. 4 tests covering bare path, qualified path on multi-schema stub, schema=Some on SQLite (silent ignore + bare table).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","assignee":"cc-pandas-2","created_at":"2026-04-25T17:32:29.202633590Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T17:39:14.126610556Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T17:39:14.124033197Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["fd90","review","schema","sql"]}
+{"id":"frankenpandas-u73po","title":"fd90.95: README Series pseudo-code uses bogus Column<Int64> generic + omits 3 fields","description":"fd90.74-94 README audit. The Series pseudo-code at lines 400-407 misrepresents the struct two ways:

1. Uses 'Column<Int64>' as if Column were generic — but crates/fp-columnar/src/lib.rs:679 declares Column as a concrete struct (dtype: DType, values: Vec<Scalar>, validity: ValidityMask). It is NOT parameterized.

2. Omits three real Series fields. crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:136 actually has: name (String), index (Index), column (Column), categorical (Option<CategoricalMetadata>), sparse (Option<SparseDType>). The pseudo-code only shows column + categorical.

Fix: rewrite the pseudo-code to match the real struct: drop the bogus Column<Int64> generic syntax (use 'Column (Int64 codes)' or 'column: Column // Int64-typed'), and add the missing name/index/sparse fields with brief annotations. Pure README change.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T09:29:10.514265379Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T09:30:18.448449314Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T09:30:18.445687224Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"frankenpandas-u7n1","title":"fp-conformance: fixture FP-P2D-128 pivot_table_unsupported_agg outdated (median now supported)","description":"Observed: tests::packet_filter_runs_dataframe_reshape_dummy_packet fails with 1/23 case failing — dataframe_pivot_table_unsupported_agg_hardened.

Fixture (crates/fp-conformance/fixtures/packets/fp_p2d_127_dataframe_pivot_table_unsupported_agg_hardened.json) expects pivot_table(aggfunc='median') to error with message containing 'not supported'. But fp-frame's pivot_table now SUPPORTS median (along with sum, mean, count, min, max, first, prod, median, var, std) — the bead path that added median to pivot_table predates this fixture.

Fix: update fixture pivot_aggfunc from 'median' to a genuinely-unsupported alias such as 'geo_mean' so the hardened-mode rejection path is still exercised. The error contract ('contains not supported') stays unchanged — fp-frame's pivot_table still emits 'pivot_table aggfunc X not supported' for any unknown aggfunc.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-22T05:00:11.564404008Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-22T05:01:33.719098322Z","closed_at":"2026-04-22T05:01:33.717171016Z","close_reason":"shipped ce6dc85: fixture pivot_aggfunc median->geo_mean (median is now a supported pivot_table aggfunc). packet_filter_runs_dataframe_reshape_dummy_packet now passes 23/23 cases.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
